00:12:38,542 --> 00:12:41,462
So now that his shadow has a couple examples

251
00:12:41,462 --> 00:12:44,603
of throwing projectiles, we're gonna go ahead

252
00:12:44,603 --> 00:12:46,903
and reload it and...

253
00:12:47,502 --> 00:12:50,923
give Derek a chance to...

254
00:12:50,923 --> 00:12:56,945
So this is going to give Derek a chance to basically

255
00:12:56,945 --> 00:12:59,206
show his shadow how to react to projectiles,

256
00:12:59,206 --> 00:13:04,087
how to jump over projectiles, how to counter projectiles.

257
00:13:04,087 --> 00:13:07,188
So now that we have some of that data,

258
00:13:07,188 --> 00:13:12,130
we're going to go ahead and commit that

259
00:13:12,130 --> 00:13:16,992
and see if the shadow is able to pick up on that as well.

260
00:13:18,627 --> 00:13:22,529
So now what we have is we have a shadow that basically

261
00:13:22,529 --> 00:13:25,171
knows how to defend against projectiles,

262
00:13:25,171 --> 00:13:28,953
knows how to defend against anti-airs,

263
00:13:28,953 --> 00:13:31,334
and also knows how to attack, attack still.

264
00:13:31,334 --> 00:13:34,036
So basically kind of in just a short amount of time,

265
00:13:34,036 --> 00:13:36,637
we've been able to create a shadow that kind of,

266
00:13:36,637 --> 00:13:39,219
we could kind of send out

267
00:13:39,219 --> 00:13:41,120
and players could fight against a bit.

268
00:13:42,779 --> 00:13:45,241
So what's also cool about this is not just that we've

269
00:13:45,241 --> 00:13:49,205
created something that's functional,

270
00:13:49,205 --> 00:13:52,969
but we've created something that was also able to capture

271
00:13:52,969 --> 00:13:54,211
Derek's style of playing.

272
00:13:54,211 --> 00:13:56,613
So we have something that's able to handle itself

273
00:13:56,613 --> 00:13:59,516
in a variety of situations, but also was able to capture

274
00:13:59,516 --> 00:14:01,378
Derek's style, which is really powerful.

275
00:14:02,138 --> 00:14:05,699
because that would work for any other player, right?

276
00:14:05,699 --> 00:14:07,939
Every player has a unique style,

277
00:14:07,939 --> 00:14:11,040
and this is going to organically pick up on that style

278
00:14:11,040 --> 00:14:12,820
without anybody having to come in

279
00:14:12,820 --> 00:14:15,161
and sort of ad hoc program that style into it.

280
00:14:15,161 --> 00:14:16,021
So now we're gonna go ahead and dig a bit

281
00:14:16,021 --> 00:14:16,421
into how this works.

282
00:14:16,421 --> 00:14:16,461
So.

283
00:14:28,818 --> 00:14:31,042
I'm gonna give a quick overview of the system.

284
00:14:31,042 --> 00:14:34,950
So, I think a really powerful way.

285
00:14:34,950 --> 00:14:35,170
Oh yeah.

286
00:14:41,787 --> 00:14:45,448
I think a really powerful way to think about this

287
00:14:45,448 --> 00:14:47,229
is to think about replay data,

288
00:14:47,229 --> 00:14:50,270
to think about replay systems that we already have.

289
00:14:50,270 --> 00:14:53,591
So with replay systems, we kind of right now just use them

290
00:14:53,591 --> 00:14:55,872
to kind of share experiences with our friends.

291
00:14:55,872 --> 00:14:57,973
So I did something really cool

292
00:14:57,973 --> 00:15:00,193
and then I want to send a replay to my friend

293
00:15:00,193 --> 00:15:01,454
so my friend can check it out.

294
00:15:01,994 --> 00:15:05,636
But what if we took that replay data that we had

295
00:15:05,636 --> 00:15:07,616
and instead of just playing it back,

296
00:15:07,616 --> 00:15:09,117
playing back all the replay data,

297
00:15:09,117 --> 00:15:11,778
what if we looked at it and we tried to play it back

298
00:15:11,778 --> 00:15:13,339
in the right situation?

299
00:15:13,339 --> 00:15:14,879
So for example, in that replay data

300
00:15:14,879 --> 00:15:17,140
we could have information recorded about

301
00:15:17,140 --> 00:15:19,741
how much health somebody had or what distance they were

302
00:15:19,741 --> 00:15:21,022
from the enemy at a certain point in time.

303
00:15:21,022 --> 00:15:24,003
We could use that information to basically

304
00:15:24,003 --> 00:15:26,784
jump around in the replay and find the right piece

305
00:15:26,784 --> 00:15:29,625
of the replay data to play back at runtime

306
00:15:29,625 --> 00:15:31,246
to produce behavior at runtime.

307
00:15:33,900 --> 00:15:36,721
So what we're seeing here is kind of a visualization

308
00:15:36,721 --> 00:15:38,221
of that process.

309
00:15:38,221 --> 00:15:40,022
We have basically a bank of a bunch

310
00:15:40,022 --> 00:15:41,522
of different replay segments,

311
00:15:41,522 --> 00:15:44,003
and the idea is that the shadow is always looking

312
00:15:44,003 --> 00:15:46,844
for the best replay segment to play back

313
00:15:46,844 --> 00:15:49,164
in context at runtime.

314
00:15:49,164 --> 00:15:51,525
So in this, we're just finding that replay segment,

315
00:15:51,525 --> 00:15:52,745
playing it back at runtime,

316
00:15:52,745 --> 00:15:54,806
and then the behavior is whatever we get

317
00:15:54,806 --> 00:15:56,867
when we play back that part of the replay at runtime.

318
00:15:59,176 --> 00:16:02,517
So a big part of this that actually makes it work

319
00:16:02,517 --> 00:16:06,839
is that sequential actions are very important.

320
00:16:06,839 --> 00:16:11,361
So even though we are jumping around in the replay,

321
00:16:11,361 --> 00:16:14,242
we're basically, we want to keep playing parts

322
00:16:14,242 --> 00:16:16,383
of the replay back that will look right.

323
00:16:16,383 --> 00:16:19,285
So we don't want to just jump around arbitrarily

324
00:16:19,285 --> 00:16:22,546
or sort of just if the world state changes just a tiny bit.

325
00:16:22,792 --> 00:16:26,234
Health changes a tiny bit, we don't just want to jump around.

326
00:16:26,234 --> 00:16:28,576
We want to basically continue playing back

327
00:16:28,576 --> 00:16:32,118
the current part of the replay until something changes

328
00:16:32,118 --> 00:16:32,579
dramatically.

329
00:16:32,579 --> 00:16:34,620
Something changes dramatically, then we'll

330
00:16:34,620 --> 00:16:38,243
consider jumping around to a different part of the replay.

331
00:16:38,243 --> 00:16:41,305
This is kind of crazy, but a lot of stuff

332
00:16:41,305 --> 00:16:44,668
is captured just by playing back parts of the replay in context.

333
00:16:44,668 --> 00:16:46,809
So lots of what we think about is

334
00:16:46,809 --> 00:16:50,452
very complicated or high-level behavior,

335
00:16:50,830 --> 00:16:52,752
planning that a player might be doing

336
00:16:52,752 --> 00:16:55,173
can be sort of captured indirectly

337
00:16:55,173 --> 00:16:57,734
by just playing back things in context at the right time.

338
00:16:57,734 --> 00:17:02,557
So we can kind of see an example of that in this next slide.

339
00:17:02,557 --> 00:17:07,060
This is an example of a player fighting his own shadow.

340
00:17:07,060 --> 00:17:10,162
And it's not really an example of what I would say

341
00:17:10,162 --> 00:17:11,683
is like a high-level player.

342
00:17:11,683 --> 00:17:14,985
It's just a player that kind of plays very stylistically.

343
00:17:14,985 --> 00:17:18,827
He jumps around like he doesn't really know what he's doing.

344
00:17:19,504 --> 00:17:21,905
And it's like he's not even trying to kill the enemy.

345
00:17:21,905 --> 00:17:24,466
But what's really cool is you can kind of clearly see

346
00:17:24,466 --> 00:17:26,527
that those kind of unique locomotions,

347
00:17:26,527 --> 00:17:28,268
they're happening on both the shadow

348
00:17:28,268 --> 00:17:31,189
and the player at the same time.

349
00:17:31,189 --> 00:17:35,071
And this is captured just by playing back those pieces

350
00:17:35,071 --> 00:17:36,791
of replay in context at the right point in time,

351
00:17:36,791 --> 00:17:38,992
and making sure to maintain the sequences.

352
00:17:38,992 --> 00:17:43,034
You would expect maybe that we would see

353
00:17:43,034 --> 00:17:45,615
sort of jarring shifts in behavior or something like that,

354
00:17:45,615 --> 00:17:47,596
but it actually, in practice, if you do it right,

355
00:17:47,596 --> 00:17:48,957
it turns out to look seamless.

356
00:17:54,003 --> 00:17:58,545
So, I want to talk about human limitations.

357
00:17:58,545 --> 00:18:03,688
So, lots of times we tend to ignore human limitations

358
00:18:03,688 --> 00:18:05,429
when we're designing traditional AI.

359
00:18:05,429 --> 00:18:08,191
In particular, in fighting games,

360
00:18:08,191 --> 00:18:11,173
one thing that we tend to ignore is reaction time.

361
00:18:11,733 --> 00:18:15,355
So the graph up here is basically just a distribution

362
00:18:15,355 --> 00:18:16,176
of reaction time.

363
00:18:16,176 --> 00:18:19,778
The data was collected from basically a very simple task

364
00:18:19,778 --> 00:18:23,700
where we would show basically a flashing green icon

365
00:18:23,700 --> 00:18:26,882
and users had to press a button as fast as possible

366
00:18:26,882 --> 00:18:28,443
when the icon flashed green.

367
00:18:29,123 --> 00:18:31,503
So how, what was the response time that it took them

368
00:18:31,503 --> 00:18:34,804
to hit the button after it flashed green?

369
00:18:34,804 --> 00:18:38,345
So, hundreds of thousands of users did this,

370
00:18:38,345 --> 00:18:40,285
and then we have their data aggregated here.

371
00:18:40,285 --> 00:18:43,446
What this graph is saying is that the vast majority

372
00:18:43,446 --> 00:18:45,527
of people have a reaction time somewhere between

373
00:18:45,527 --> 00:18:47,187
200 and 320 milliseconds.

374
00:18:47,187 --> 00:18:50,968
So why this might be important for a fighting game,

375
00:18:50,968 --> 00:18:52,248
and in particular Killer Instinct,

376
00:18:52,248 --> 00:18:55,329
is because the vast majority of actions in Killer Instinct,

377
00:18:55,329 --> 00:18:57,670
the vast majority of things like attacking an opponent

378
00:18:57,670 --> 00:18:58,410
or hitting an opponent.

379
00:18:58,962 --> 00:19:03,066
actually hit in less than that amount of time.

380
00:19:03,066 --> 00:19:05,768
So what that means is that a big part of the game,

381
00:19:05,768 --> 00:19:08,050
almost half of the game, is not reactable.

382
00:19:08,050 --> 00:19:09,491
And yet when people play the game,

383
00:19:09,491 --> 00:19:11,713
it seems like it makes sense.

384
00:19:11,713 --> 00:19:13,594
People feel like they're doing something.

385
00:19:13,594 --> 00:19:15,095
It feels compelling, they're playing it,

386
00:19:15,095 --> 00:19:17,157
and they feel like they're in control.

387
00:19:17,157 --> 00:19:21,140
But if the stuff isn't reactable, how is that possible?

388
00:19:21,140 --> 00:19:23,462
Well, it turns out that

389
00:19:24,385 --> 00:19:27,227
for non-reactable situations like the situation

390
00:19:27,227 --> 00:19:29,569
on the right, the player is basically playing

391
00:19:29,569 --> 00:19:30,870
a guessing game.

392
00:19:30,870 --> 00:19:33,772
So you can see the enemy basically doing a pressure string,

393
00:19:33,772 --> 00:19:37,215
a string of attacks while you're blocking.

394
00:19:37,215 --> 00:19:39,176
And you have to basically guess

395
00:19:39,176 --> 00:19:40,997
when the enemy is going to stop doing,

396
00:19:40,997 --> 00:19:42,979
if the enemy is going to stop doing the pressure string

397
00:19:42,979 --> 00:19:45,060
or if he's going to continue doing the pressure string.

398
00:19:45,060 --> 00:19:49,584
And that guess lets you know when you should do

399
00:19:49,584 --> 00:19:51,385
tiger fury in the middle of the pressure string.

400
00:19:51,905 --> 00:19:55,968
The thing is that you can't react to the enemy stopping the pressure string.

401
00:19:55,968 --> 00:20:00,250
So you have to guess based on the history of fighting this opponent in the match,

402
00:20:00,250 --> 00:20:03,352
how aggressive is he, how long is he going to continue the pressure string.

403
00:20:03,352 --> 00:20:08,395
This is kind of what people are talking about when they talk about mind games in a fighting game.

404
00:20:08,935 --> 00:20:12,917
And this kind of mind game, this kind of thing

405
00:20:12,917 --> 00:20:16,298
that's happening at the margin of human reaction time

406
00:20:16,298 --> 00:20:17,718
doesn't just happen in fighting games.

407
00:20:17,718 --> 00:20:19,458
It happens in other competitive games.

408
00:20:19,458 --> 00:20:22,319
In Counter-Strike, there's lots of headshots

409
00:20:22,319 --> 00:20:24,540
that seem impossible, basically.

410
00:20:24,540 --> 00:20:28,161
But then when you look at what's really going on,

411
00:20:28,161 --> 00:20:31,322
it's basically high-level players pre-aiming

412
00:20:31,322 --> 00:20:35,223
and pre-shooting because they know that their enemy

413
00:20:35,223 --> 00:20:36,804
is going to end up in a certain location

414
00:20:36,804 --> 00:20:37,944
at a certain point in time.

415
00:20:38,509 --> 00:20:43,014
So, basically, keeping in mind,

416
00:20:43,014 --> 00:20:45,016
reaction time is very important

417
00:20:45,016 --> 00:20:46,398
in designing these kinds of AIs.

418
00:20:46,398 --> 00:20:48,100
Otherwise, you'll miss out, basically,

419
00:20:48,100 --> 00:20:50,323
on all this interesting behavior

420
00:20:50,323 --> 00:20:55,288
that players have at those margins of reaction time.

421
00:20:55,288 --> 00:20:55,368
So,

422
00:20:57,323 --> 00:20:59,085
Because of the way the shadow system works,

423
00:20:59,085 --> 00:21:00,846
because we're just capturing replay data

424
00:21:00,846 --> 00:21:02,948
and playing it back in context,

425
00:21:02,948 --> 00:21:04,969
we are capturing when players react

426
00:21:04,969 --> 00:21:06,250
and when players don't react

427
00:21:06,250 --> 00:21:07,972
based on the state of the world.

428
00:21:07,972 --> 00:21:11,114
So that means that if a player doesn't react

429
00:21:11,114 --> 00:21:13,656
when, doesn't react in certain situations,

430
00:21:13,656 --> 00:21:16,718
doesn't respond to an attack in certain situations,

431
00:21:16,718 --> 00:21:18,260
we don't have any data for it,

432
00:21:18,260 --> 00:21:21,442
so we never get basically, you know,

433
00:21:21,442 --> 00:21:23,043
the instant hit headshot or something like that

434
00:21:23,043 --> 00:21:25,285
because we just have what the player did in context.

435
00:21:26,107 --> 00:21:28,911
we get this human limitation just as a consequence

436
00:21:28,911 --> 00:21:31,054
of how the system works and records data.

437
00:21:31,054 --> 00:21:32,415
So this is kind of an example from Counter-Strike

438
00:21:32,415 --> 00:21:36,341
of sort of what happens when you kind of ignore

439
00:21:36,341 --> 00:21:42,169
human limitations, just kind of the traditional example

440
00:21:42,169 --> 00:21:43,731
of like an aimbot or something.

441
00:21:47,398 --> 00:21:50,421
So somebody just walks, gets headshot instantly,

442
00:21:50,421 --> 00:21:51,802
it's super frustrating.

443
00:21:51,802 --> 00:21:54,945
The way that we traditionally deal with this, right,

444
00:21:54,945 --> 00:21:59,649
is we make it less frustrating by adjusting the aim accuracy

445
00:21:59,649 --> 00:22:01,951
or randomly dropping shots occasionally

446
00:22:01,951 --> 00:22:03,233
or something like that.

447
00:22:03,233 --> 00:22:06,095
And that can work great for difficulty adjustment,

448
00:22:06,095 --> 00:22:07,917
but it doesn't capture

449
00:22:08,958 --> 00:22:13,120
human limitations in the same way that humans

450
00:22:13,120 --> 00:22:13,800
have those limitations.

451
00:22:13,800 --> 00:22:16,122
So like we were saying with pre-aiming,

452
00:22:16,122 --> 00:22:18,383
it's possible in Counter-Strike for players

453
00:22:18,383 --> 00:22:20,984
to get an impossible shot,

454
00:22:20,984 --> 00:22:23,445
I mean a shot that's below reaction time.

455
00:22:23,445 --> 00:22:26,427
But if we just do something like have a difficulty slider,

456
00:22:26,427 --> 00:22:30,169
it doesn't capture that aspect of human behavior.

457
00:22:31,229 --> 00:22:34,692
So what we want to talk about now is decision making.

458
00:22:34,692 --> 00:22:37,514
Basically, what is it like when you build an AI

459
00:22:37,514 --> 00:22:40,136
with a shadow system versus building an AI

460
00:22:40,136 --> 00:22:42,338
with basically traditional methods?

461
00:22:42,829 --> 00:22:44,831
So with the traditional approach,

462
00:22:44,831 --> 00:22:47,373
we kind of decide on some stuff that we want to create.

463
00:22:47,373 --> 00:22:50,075
We say, OK, let's make a aggressive AI.

464
00:22:50,075 --> 00:22:51,196
Let's make a defensive AI.

465
00:22:51,196 --> 00:22:55,639
And then we either use some ad hoc solution,

466
00:22:55,639 --> 00:22:57,921
or we use a behavior tree, or we use a state machine

467
00:22:57,921 --> 00:23:00,143
or something to try to explicitly encode

468
00:23:00,143 --> 00:23:02,625
those behaviors that we're interested in creating.

469
00:23:04,612 --> 00:23:07,734
So this stuff works great, obviously.

470
00:23:07,734 --> 00:23:09,715
It's what we always do.

471
00:23:09,715 --> 00:23:12,998
We can get a lot of range and difficulty and everything.

472
00:23:12,998 --> 00:23:16,380
One problem with it is that we're always

473
00:23:16,380 --> 00:23:17,921
limited by developer resources.

474
00:23:17,921 --> 00:23:19,362
There's only so much we can do.

475
00:23:19,362 --> 00:23:23,065
We have to decide what things we want to model,

476
00:23:23,065 --> 00:23:25,306
and then somebody has to sit down and do them.

477
00:23:25,867 --> 00:23:28,911
And like we've talked about earlier in the introduction,

478
00:23:28,911 --> 00:23:31,615
obviously the game continues to evolve

479
00:23:31,615 --> 00:23:32,696
after being released.

480
00:23:32,696 --> 00:23:35,400
And if we don't have some solution that's sort of automatic

481
00:23:35,400 --> 00:23:37,803
we're not going to be able to keep up with the game

482
00:23:37,803 --> 00:23:38,725
after we release it.

483
00:23:40,951 --> 00:23:44,574
This is opposed, as opposed to the shadow system

484
00:23:44,574 --> 00:23:47,397
where instead of basically explicitly creating

485
00:23:47,397 --> 00:23:51,420
these behaviors, explicitly creating a offensive

486
00:23:51,420 --> 00:23:55,103
or a defensive AI, the designer or the developer

487
00:23:55,103 --> 00:23:57,505
takes a higher level approach and designs things

488
00:23:57,505 --> 00:24:00,148
called similarity functions, weights, and heuristics.

489
00:24:00,148 --> 00:24:02,990
And we'll dig into what each of those are in a second.

490
00:24:03,430 --> 00:24:05,812
So first of all, there's this idea of similarity.

491
00:24:05,812 --> 00:24:07,513
When I was talking about the concept of picking

492
00:24:07,513 --> 00:24:09,535
the right part of the replay, I was talking about

493
00:24:09,535 --> 00:24:13,898
we need to find something from our bank of replays

494
00:24:13,898 --> 00:24:16,059
that is similar to the current situation.

495
00:24:16,059 --> 00:24:19,322
So what similar means is kind of defined by the designer.

496
00:24:19,322 --> 00:24:23,805
So you can imagine kind of a simple Euclidean idea

497
00:24:23,805 --> 00:24:26,347
of similarity, where you have two dimensions of health

498
00:24:26,347 --> 00:24:27,047
and distance.

499
00:24:27,447 --> 00:24:30,010
And each of those dots in the graph is basically,

500
00:24:30,010 --> 00:24:32,151
you can imagine, a replay segment.

501
00:24:32,151 --> 00:24:35,594
So for example, the one that has 100 health

502
00:24:35,594 --> 00:24:39,197
and 0.5 distance corresponds to a part of the replay

503
00:24:39,197 --> 00:24:43,841
where the enemy's world state was that.

504
00:24:43,841 --> 00:24:50,847
So think of the dot on the far right as being the current

505
00:24:51,585 --> 00:24:55,649
as being the current runtime situation, basically.

506
00:24:55,649 --> 00:24:57,510
So what we want to do is we want to find the dot,

507
00:24:57,510 --> 00:25:00,853
the replay segment that's closest to that runtime situation,

508
00:25:00,853 --> 00:25:03,195
which happens to be the one that is closest to that,

509
00:25:03,195 --> 00:25:08,499
that's immediately to the left of it.

510
00:25:10,597 --> 00:25:12,140
Basically, it's up to the designer

511
00:25:12,140 --> 00:25:14,183
to say what that means.

512
00:25:14,183 --> 00:25:16,226
In this case, it was just the Euclidean distance.

513
00:25:16,226 --> 00:25:18,029
But it could be just absolute value,

514
00:25:18,029 --> 00:25:20,753
or it could be some crazy thing that a designer or developer

515
00:25:20,753 --> 00:25:21,755
comes up with.

516
00:25:21,755 --> 00:25:24,439
You just need to come up with some idea of similarity.

517
00:25:25,400 --> 00:25:28,322
So once you've created your similarity metrics

518
00:25:28,322 --> 00:25:31,866
for health distance or whatever you're interested in,

519
00:25:31,866 --> 00:25:34,989
whatever you're interested in using

520
00:25:34,989 --> 00:25:36,810
to compare two different situations,

521
00:25:36,810 --> 00:25:39,553
you need to combine all of those similarity metrics

522
00:25:39,553 --> 00:25:41,294
to basically get an aggregate score.

523
00:25:41,835 --> 00:25:43,835
So you can imagine that you have things like health,

524
00:25:43,835 --> 00:25:45,596
distance, time, or meter, ammo.

525
00:25:45,596 --> 00:25:47,777
Now that you have all these different similarity metrics,

526
00:25:47,777 --> 00:25:49,697
how do they matter relative to each other?

527
00:25:49,697 --> 00:25:51,498
Is health more important than ammo?

528
00:25:51,498 --> 00:25:54,459
Is timer more important than distance?

529
00:25:54,459 --> 00:25:56,519
So another role of a designer or developer

530
00:25:56,519 --> 00:25:59,000
when using the system is to basically adjust

531
00:25:59,000 --> 00:26:02,181
all of these weights so that they have

532
00:26:02,181 --> 00:26:03,921
the right relative impact.

533
00:26:03,921 --> 00:26:07,662
So this is something that kind of requires domain expertise.

534
00:26:07,662 --> 00:26:10,663
It requires kind of an intuition for how the system works.

535
00:26:11,003 --> 00:26:14,436
You might just have knowledge because of how well you know the game,

536
00:26:14,436 --> 00:26:17,106
that distance is more important than health, for example.

537
00:26:19,102 --> 00:26:23,645
So it's worthwhile to think about how this kind of approach

538
00:26:23,645 --> 00:26:25,746
could be used in a different kind of game.

539
00:26:25,746 --> 00:26:28,648
So if we think about something like Counter-Strike,

540
00:26:28,648 --> 00:26:31,850
instead of using the traditional difficulty sliders of,

541
00:26:31,850 --> 00:26:34,992
okay, maybe I'll fail to hit the enemy every once in a while,

542
00:26:34,992 --> 00:26:37,373
or maybe I'll fail to get a headshot every once in a while,

543
00:26:37,373 --> 00:26:40,835
what if we track things like visibility,

544
00:26:40,835 --> 00:26:43,277
like maybe there's occluding objects on the screen,

545
00:26:43,277 --> 00:26:45,638
or how far away the opponent is,

546
00:26:45,638 --> 00:26:48,780
or what the relative angle is to the opponent.

547
00:26:49,201 --> 00:26:51,282
If we have all that information being tracked

548
00:26:51,282 --> 00:26:53,203
for each of the players and then what they did

549
00:26:53,203 --> 00:26:56,105
when the world state, what they did

550
00:26:56,105 --> 00:26:57,225
in those different world states,

551
00:26:57,225 --> 00:26:59,166
then we can capture things like some players

552
00:26:59,166 --> 00:27:02,388
being less sensitive to the angle of the opponent,

553
00:27:02,388 --> 00:27:04,910
some players not just having tunnel vision basically.

